e on the steps being taken by the Indian Government to strengthen its northern frontier defenses.\n\nThe army operational headquarters at Jorhat in Assam State reported on 19 November that it had ordered \"an increase in the average personnel strength of Indian border outposts in the three frontier divisions--Kameng, Subansiri, and Siang--from eight to twelve with immediate effect.\"\n\nThe deputy inspector general of West Bengal's Intelligence Bureau stated that there now are a total of 86 border outposts in the four Tibetan frontier divisions of the Northeast Frontier Agency (NEFA), including 24 new ones. The northern border of NEFA is approximately 500 miles long.\n\nArmy reserves in Kalimpong and Lebong also had been increased recently by 600 and 500 men respectively.\n\nDefenses in northeastern India have been further strengthened by the recent transfer of an infantry division from Punjab State to Assam. This will bring ground force strength in this region to about 50,000 troops, comprising the equivalent of two army divisions and 14 battalions of local security forces. Army commands had been ordered to recall all reserves to their units gradually for training. There are about 50,000 of these reserves with 10 to 18 years of active service", "token_count": 208, "token_end_0based": 207, "token_start_0based": 0, "token_text": "india strengthens border defenses firm evidence on the steps being taken by the indian government to strengthen its northern frontier defenses the army operational headquarters at jorhat in assam state reported on 19 november that it had ordered an increase in the average personnel strength of indian border outposts in the three frontier divisions kameng subansiri and siang from eight to twelve with immediate effect the deputy inspector general of west bengal's intelligence bureau stated that there now are a total of 86 border outposts in the four tibetan frontier divisions of the northeast frontier agency nefa including 24 new ones the northern border of nefa is approximately 500 miles long army reserves in kalimpong and lebong also had been increased recently by 600 and 500 men respectively defenses in northeastern india have been further strengthened by the recent transfer of an infantry division from punjab state to assam this will bring ground force strength in this region to about 50 000 troops comprising the equivalent of two army divisions and 14 battalions of local security forces army commands had been ordered to recall all reserves to their units gradually for training there are about 50 000 of these reserves with 10 to 18 years of active service", "unred_source_page": 12}
